excerpt: Monumental 19th-century church featuring ornate neo-Gothic styling & city views from its towers.
detail_description: The Basílica del Voto Nacional is a stunning 19th-century church in Quito's historic center, known for its ornate neo-Gothic architecture. The church features intricate gargoyles and spires, offering visitors the chance to climb to the top for breathtaking city views. It appeals to architecture enthusiasts, religious history buffs, and those seeking unparalleled panoramic vistas. Climbing the steep and narrow staircases to the towers is a must for an unforgettable experience.
name: Basílica del Voto Nacional

excerpt: Rounded hill, a local landmark, with a 41m aluminum statue of the Virgin of Quito at its summit.
detail_description: El Panecillo is a rounded hill in Quito, Ecuador, featuring a 41m aluminum statue of the Virgin of Quito at its summit. It overlooks the city and offers stunning panoramic views, making it a popular spot for photography enthusiasts and cultural explorers. Visitors can enjoy peaceful sunrise or golden hour experiences here. To reach El Panecillo, it's recommended to take a taxi or use guided tour services due to its popularity and potential crowding.
name: El Panecillo

excerpt: Biking, soccer & basketball are popular in this vast park featuring a pond with paddle boats.
detail_description: Parque La Carolina is a vast 67-hectare park located in the northern part of the city, offering a wide range of activities and attractions. Visitors can enjoy biking, soccer, basketball, and even rent paddle boats to explore the park's pond. The park also features football fields, running tracks, playgrounds, and a large skatepark. Additionally, it houses the Quito Exhibition Center and Botanical Gardens.
name: Parque La Carolina

excerpt: Museum honoring Latin Americans with extensive artworks by Oswaldo Guayasamín & artifacts.
detail_description: Capilla del Hombre is a museum in Quito, Ecuador, dedicated to the celebrated artist Oswaldo Guayasamín. The museum showcases his impressive paintings and sculptures, as well as collections of pre-Columbian and colonial artifacts. Visitors can explore five cultural spaces managed by the Guayasamin Foundation, including the Guayasamin House-Museum and the Maruja Monteverde Hall of Temporary Exhibitions.
name: Capilla del Hombre
address: Mariano Calvache E18-94 y, Lorenzo Chávez 170135, Quito, Ecuador

excerpt: Attraction with a cablecar lift to the top of a mountain for high-altitude hikes & panoramic views.
detail_description: The TelefériQo Cable Car offers a thrilling ride to the top of a mountain, providing access to high-altitude hikes and stunning panoramic views. Situated on the hills west of the capital, this ski-lift-type gondola takes visitors to a lofty vantage point, offering an unparalleled perspective of the surrounding landscape.
name: TelefériQo Cable Car

excerpt: Quito, Ecuador's capital, sits high in the Andean foothills at an altitude of 2,850m. Constructed on the foundations of an ancient Incan city, it’s known for its well-preserved colonial center, rich with 16th- and 17th-century churches and other structures blending European, Moorish and indigenous styles. These include the cathedral, in the Plaza Grande square, and ultra-ornate Compañia de Jesús Jesuit church.
detail_description: Quito, the capital of Ecuador, is perched high in the Andean foothills at an elevation of 2,850m. The city boasts a well-preserved colonial center with 16th- and 17th-century churches and structures that blend European, Moorish, and indigenous architectural styles. The Plaza Grande square features the impressive cathedral and the ornate Compañia de Jesús Jesuit church.
name: Quito

detail_description: Cd Mitad del Mundo, also known as Middle of the World City, is located just north of Quito and is a significant landmark marking the equator that passes through Ecuador. The complex features a monument, museum, exhibition spaces, and the famous line itself. Visitors can take pictures straddling the line that gives the country its name while learning about the first measurements made to discover Earth's shape as an oblate spheroid.
name: Cd Mitad del Mundo

detail_description: Located just over 13 miles from the Equator, Mitad del Mundo in Quito, Ecuador offers visitors the unique opportunity to straddle both hemispheres. At this site, you can explore the monument and ascend to a viewing platform for stunning panoramic views. Additionally, there's an ethnographical museum and a scale model of Quito's old town to immerse yourself in.
name: Coffee shop Mitad del Mundo

excerpt: Sprawling green space with Japanese gardens, a bonsai collection & a boating lagoon with fountains.
detail_description: Quito Botanical Gardens, nestled within La Carolina Park, offers a delightful escape into nature. The garden showcases the diverse ecosystems of Ecuador, featuring replicas of coastal, Andean, and Amazon environments. Visitors can explore two impressive greenhouses housing exquisite orchids and intriguing carnivorous plants. Additionally, the garden boasts a bonsai collection and a serene boating lagoon with charming fountains. It's an ideal spot to immerse oneself in the country's natural beauty without leaving the capital city.
name: Quito Botanical Gardens
address: INTERIOR PARQUE, PASAJE # 34, Rumipamba E6-264 Y, Quito 170135, Ecuador

excerpt: Gondola lift up the side of Pichincha Volcano, with an observation deck, dining & shops at the top.
detail_description: The Teleférico de Quito is a thrilling gondola lift that takes you up the side of Pichincha Volcano, offering breathtaking views and an exhilarating ride. As one of the highest aerial lifts globally, it provides stunning vistas over Quito as it ascends to 4100 meters and reaches Cruz Loma. While there are some pricey cafes and shops at the top, the main draw is the epic panoramic views of the city and its surroundings.
name: Teleférico de Quito

excerpt: Stone monument along the equator & a plaza where visitors can stand with a foot in each hemisphere.
detail_description: Middle of the World City, located in the parish of San Antonio de Pichincha just 14 kilometers from Quito, is a significant historical site where visitors can straddle the equator. At this unique location, tourists can stand with one foot in each hemisphere and engage in activities such as balancing an egg on a nail and observing the Coriolis effect. Additionally, visitors can explore the Inti Nan Museum to learn about the scientific and cultural aspects of the Equator Line.
name: Middle of the World
address: Av. Manuel Córdova Galarza SN, Quito 170311, Ecuador

excerpt: Cobblestone alley featuring restored historic buildings & a lively bar scene in the evening.
detail_description: Calle La Ronda, located in the heart of Quito's historic center, is a picturesque cobblestone street adorned with vibrant buildings, art galleries, and artisanal shops. This charming alley is a hub for traditional music, dance performances, and exceptional culinary experiences. Visitors can immerse themselves in the authentic ambiance of Calle La Ronda while enjoying live music and interactive workshops. In the evening, the street comes alive with local artisans showcasing their crafts and lively bar scenes.
name: Calle La Ronda

excerpt: 16th-century domed church with neoclassical architecture & 4 colorful, dramatic chapels.
detail_description: The Catedral Metropolitana de Quito is a 16th-century domed church with neoclassical architecture and four colorful, dramatic chapels. It is one of the oldest churches in South America and a must-visit in the historic center of Quito.
name: Quito Metropolitan Cathedral

excerpt: Vast collection of pre-Columbian art & artifacts in stylish, contemporary displays.
detail_description: Casa del Alabado Pre-Columbian Art Museum, located in Quito's old district, showcases a vast collection of over 5,000 pre-Columbian art and artifacts. The museum is housed in a restored colonial house and features stylish contemporary displays with interactive explanatory screens throughout. It prioritizes the aesthetics of the objects over historical topics, focusing on the social processes of pre-Hispanic Ecuador.
name: Casa del Alabado Pre-Columbian Art Museum

excerpt: Monumental baroque church with an interior featuring elaborate paintings & sculpture.
detail_description: The San Francisco Catholic Church in Quito is a grand baroque church known for its ornate interior featuring intricate paintings and sculptures. It is part of the historic center of Quito, which also includes other notable attractions such as the Compania de Jesus church, Basilica del Voto Nacional church, Catedral Primada de Quito, and Santo Domingo church. The area also boasts landmarks like La Plaza Grande and Carondelet Palace.
name: Basilica and Convent of San Francisco
address: Plaza de San Francisco, Cuenca 477, Quito 170401, Ecuador

excerpt: Large, tree-filled park with paths, weekend art exhibitions & vendors selling food & crafts.
detail_description: Parque El Ejido is a large, lush park with walking paths and weekend art exhibitions. It offers a vibrant atmosphere with food and craft vendors. The park is located near the old town and the lively La Mariscal district, making it a central part of Quito's cultural scene. In addition to exploring the park, visitors can also enjoy nearby attractions such as modern mega-malls for shopping, historic downtown churches, museums, and restaurants.
name: Parque El Ejido

excerpt: Colorful dorms & private rooms in a basic hostel offering an eatery, plus a terrace with city views.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Quito, The Secret Garden offers a vibrant and welcoming atmosphere for travelers seeking both comfort and community. This locally-run hostel is situated on a charming cobblestone street just a few blocks from the main plaza, making it an ideal base for exploring the city. Guests can choose from colorful dorms or private rooms, all designed with simplicity in mind. One of the standout features of The Secret Garden is its stunning rooftop terrace, which boasts breathtaking views over Quito.
name: The Secret Garden Quito
address: Street, J. de Antepara &, Quito 170136, Ecuador

excerpt: Exhibits on Andean indigenous culture in an imposing stone building designed by artist Ortega Maila.
detail_description: Museo Templo del Sol Pintor Cristobal Ortega Maila is a cultural museum showcasing Ecuadorian art, history, and indigenous culture. The imposing stone building was designed by artist Ortega Maila and features pieces that delve into Andean heritage. Visitors can explore the rich history and art of Ecuador while admiring the work of the renowned painter Alvaro Ortega.
name: Museo Templo del Sol Pintor Cristobal Ortega Maila
address: En el Mirador de la reserva geobotanica pululahua Manuel Córdova Galarza E28 y, Eduardo Kingman Oe12 174, Quito 170603, Ecuador

excerpt: Iconic baroque church, built from 1605–1765, known for its elaborately carved, gilded interior.
detail_description: The Church of the Society of Jesus, also known as La Compania de Jesus, is a remarkable baroque church in Quito, Ecuador. Its construction began in 1605 and was completed in 1765. The interior is adorned with elaborate carvings and gilded with gold leaf, creating a breathtaking sight that has earned it the reputation of being one of the most beautiful churches in Ecuador.
name: Church of the Society of Jesus

excerpt: Place of worship including a neo-Gothic altarpiece, with 16th & 17th-century paintings & sculptures.
detail_description: Iglesia de Santo Domingo, located in the historic center of Quito, is a significant place of worship with a rich history dating back to 1540. The church features a stunning neo-Gothic altarpiece and houses an array of 16th and 17th-century paintings and sculptures. The interior is adorned with intricate cedar carvings covered in gold leaf, along with valuable religious artwork.
name: Iglesia de Santo Domingo

excerpt: Contemporary museum with exhibits highlighting the scientific & social significance of water.
detail_description: Nestled in the picturesque El Placer neighborhood, Yaku Water Museum offers a captivating journey into the world of water, highlighting its scientific and social significance. Set against the backdrop of Pichincha volcano, this contemporary museum stands on the site of Quito's first water treatment plant. It serves as an interactive space where visitors can explore the multifaceted nature of water through innovative exhibits that blend science, art, history, and spirituality.
name: Yaku Water Museum

detail_description: Mercado Central in Quito, Ecuador is a historic and vibrant market dating back to 1950. It's located on Pichincha Avenue and is known for its gastronomy and the friendly vendors. The market offers a colorful array of tropical fruits like papayas, mangoes, and pineapples. Additionally, it features traditional healers called curanderas who perform rituals for good fortune.
name: Mercado Central

detail_description: Plaza Foch, located in the La Mariscal neighborhood at the center of Quito, is a vibrant plaza known for its bustling nightlife. In the mornings, it's quiet, but as night falls, the area comes alive with numerous bars and restaurants. While some caution against dining at Plaza Foch due to high prices and mediocre food, it's still a great starting point for bar hopping and experiencing the energetic nightlife.
name: Plaza Foch

excerpt: Elevated nature area with wooded trails & viewing decks overlooking the city, plus native alpacas.
detail_description: Parque Metropolitano Guanguiltagua is a sprawling urban park located in Quito, offering a peaceful retreat from the city's hustle and bustle. Situated at 2,890 meters above sea level, this expansive 557-hectare park features lush green spaces, well-maintained walking trails, and stunning viewpoints that showcase the natural beauty of the Andean landscape. Visitors can immerse themselves in diverse environments including dense forests and serene ponds while enjoying birdwatching opportunities.
name: Parque Metropolitano Guangüiltagua

excerpt: La Floresta is an electoral parish or district of Quito, the capital city of Ecuador. The parish was established as a result of the October 2006 political elections when the city was divided into 19 urban electoral parishes. Wikipedia.
detail_description: La Floresta, an electoral parish in Quito, Ecuador, emerged after the 2006 elections. This vibrant neighborhood offers a unique experience away from typical tourist spots. Visitors can explore numerous coffee shops, galleries, and street art while also enjoying an artisanal brewery. Additionally, La Floresta is home to Ocho y Medio, an indie movie theater and cafe with a view of an eerie abandoned house.
name: La Floresta

excerpt: Sprawling historic district featuring over 100 Spanish colonial & neoclassical buildings.
detail_description: The Quito Historic Center is a captivating area that showcases the rich cultural and architectural heritage of Ecuador's capital. As a UNESCO World Heritage Site, it boasts over 100 well-preserved Spanish colonial and neoclassical buildings, making it one of the finest examples of colonial districts in Latin America. Strolling through its charming cobblestone streets, visitors can admire stunning churches like La Iglesia de la Compania de Jesus, renowned for its breathtaking baroque interior adorned with gold leaf.
name: Quito Historic Center

excerpt: La Floresta is a busy residential and college district home to sushi bars and Italian, Mexican, and Ecuadorian bistros. The Ochoymedio cinema shows arthouse and international films in a venue with a hip cafe. Indigenous artifacts like ceramics, hunting tools, and shrunken heads are on display at the Museo Amazónico, while the Gustavo Orcés natural history museum has dinosaur models and taxidermy.
detail_description: La Floresta, a vibrant neighborhood in Quito, is known for its diverse culinary scene featuring sushi bars and various international bistros. The area also boasts cultural attractions such as the Ochoymedio cinema, which screens arthouse films and houses a trendy cafe. Visitors can explore indigenous artifacts at the Museo Amazónico and discover natural history exhibits at the Gustavo Orcés museum.
name: La Floresta

excerpt: Guápulo is a district of Quito, Ecuador, also called an electoral parish. The parish was established as a result of the October 2004 political elections when the city was divided into 19 urban electoral parishes. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Guapulo, nestled near the La Floresta district in Quito, offers a less touristy experience with its mix of whitewashed and vibrantly colored buildings. The Guapulo Colonial Church and Convent is a must-see attraction in this neighborhood. As you descend the steep cobblestone path towards the church, you'll encounter bohemian culture exemplified by places like Pizzeria Ananke, which offers a picturesque dining experience overlooking the illuminated valley at night.
name: Guapulo

excerpt: Museum showcasing exhibits from places on the equator, plus equator-related science experiments.
detail_description: The Intiñan Equator Museum, located in San Antonio de Pichincha, is a fascinating day trip destination. Situated at what is believed to be the exact location of the equator, the museum offers an array of exhibits and science experiments related to this unique geographical feature. Visitors can explore a diverse collection of archaeological artifacts from various cultures and enjoy informative guided tours that delve into Ecuador's ecosystems and indigenous peoples.
name: Intiñan Equator Museum
address: Manuel Cordova Galarza, Av. Manuel Córdova Galarza, Quito, Ecuador

excerpt: Hilltop statue of a winged Virgin Mary made of aluminum, on a pedestal & standing 30 m. tall.
detail_description: The Virgin of the Panecillo is a 30-meter-tall aluminum statue of the winged Virgin Mary, located on a hill overlooking Quito's Old Town. According to local legend, the statue faces north to bless that part of the city while her back is turned to the south, symbolizing wealth disparity. The road leading to the statue winds around El Panecillo hill, offering panoramic views of Quito.
name: Virgin of the Panecillo

excerpt: Amusement park with kiddie & family rides as well as a roller coaster, bumper cars & haunted house.
detail_description: Vulqano Park is an amusement park located at the base of Cruz Loma, near Quito's cableway. It offers a variety of rides and attractions suitable for both kids and families, including a roller coaster, bumper cars, haunted house, canopy ride, carrousel, slides and more. Visitors can easily reach the park by booking a yellow taxi through apps like Cabify or Uber. The park has quickly become one of Quito's top entertainment options.
name: Vulqano Park

excerpt: Forested park with hiking trails & an ornate, 19th-century glasshouse full of rare trees & orchids.
detail_description: Parque Itchimbía, located in Quito, is a forested park offering hiking trails and an ornate 19th-century glasshouse filled with rare trees and orchids. Situated on a hillside, the park provides panoramic views of the cityscape and serves as a popular recreational area and cultural venue. It appeals to outdoor enthusiasts, art lovers, and families seeking open spaces and entertainment. The park hosts various cultural activities such as live performances, art exhibitions, and festivals.
name: Parque Itchimbía

detail_description: The Centro Cultural Metropolitano is a vibrant cultural center located in Quito, housed in a historic 400-year-old complex. It serves as the focal point of the city's artistic life, offering a diverse program of exhibitions, conferences, and concerts. The center is dedicated to promoting and celebrating Ecuador's rich cultural heritage. Visitors can explore temporary exhibitions on the first floor and the Museo Alberto Mena Caamano on the second floor, showcasing contemporary and colonial art.
name: Centro Cultural Metropolitano

detail_description: The Quito Astronomical Observatory is a research institute of EPN, the National Polytechnic School in Quito, Ecuador. The observatory has been in operation since 1864 and is one of the oldest on the continent. It houses a museum of historical instruments, including pendulums, sextants, chronometers and other devices. In 2020, after working with them during early development stages, it was able to gain an understanding of science at Ecuador through this facility.
name: Astronomical Observatory of Quito
address: QFPW+2XW, Dentro del Parque de, Av Gran Colombia y, Av. 10 de Agosto, Quito 170403, Ecuador

detail_description: Nestled beside the historic double-towered Carmen Alto Church, the Museo del Carmen Alto invites visitors into a world steeped in reverence and history. As you approach its grand square foyer, there's an undeniable sense of entering a significant cultural landmark. Inside, the museum beautifully showcases Carmelite Heritage Art while offering insights into the daily lives of the Descalza Carmelite sisters and celebrating Mariana de Jesus, an Ecuadorian saint and heroine.
name: Museo del Carmen Alto

excerpt: Active stratovolcano with hiking & climbing, plus the panoramic TelefériQo gondola at its foothills.
detail_description: Pichincha Volcano is an active stratovolcano located in the Andes Mountains, with opportunities for hiking and climbing. At its foothills, you can take the panoramic TelefériQo gondola which offers stunning views of the surrounding area. The city nearby is nestled in the basins of Guayllabamba River and is divided into three topographic zones: Central Zone, Southern Zone, and Northern Zone.
name: Pichincha Volcano

excerpt: Named for a church on its edge, this square was built upon the site of Emperor Atahualpa’s palace.
detail_description: Plaza de San Francisco, named after a nearby church, is located in the heart of Quito's Old Town. It was built on the site of Emperor Atahualpa’s palace and offers a glimpse into the city's rich history. Staying near this square provides easy access to the vibrant city center and its attractions.
name: Plaza de San Francisco

detail_description: La Mariscal, also known as Mariscal Foch or La Foch, is a vibrant neighborhood in Quito that offers budget accommodation options and attracts backpackers, remote workers, and expats. Centered around the Plaza Foch, it is renowned for its lively restaurants and nightlife scene. The Mercado Artesanal La Mariscal is a great place to find artisanal goods such as alpaca blankets and Ecuadorian chocolates.
name: LA MARISCAL

detail_description: Located in the heart of Quito at Plaza Grande, Los Sanduches de la Plaza Grande is a must-visit spot for both locals and tourists. The plaza itself offers a myriad of activities, from watching the changing of the guard to exploring historical landmarks like the Presidential Palace and La Compania. However, what sets this place apart is its delicious sandwiches. Served on delightful baguette-style bread, these sandwiches are not only tasty but also reasonably priced.
name: Los Sanduches de la Plaza Grande

detail_description: The Historic Center of Quito is a captivating area located at the foot of a northern hill. It is renowned for its stunning churches that showcase remarkable architecture and historical significance.
name: Historic Center of Quito

excerpt: Museum dedicated to sculptor & painter Oswaldo Guayasamín in the artist's former hillside home.
detail_description: Fundación Guayasamin is a museum and former home of the renowned Ecuadorian artist Oswaldo Guayasamín. The museum includes the Capilla del Hombre, which offers a unique art experience showcasing the struggle and oppression of Latin American Indians through Guayasamín's evocative paintings. Influenced by Pablo Picasso and the Cubists, Guayasamín is known for filtering 20th-century tragedies through his artwork.
name: Fundación Guayasamin
address: Mariano Calvache E18-94 y, Quito 170516, Ecuador

excerpt: Grand plaza & park in the heart of old Quito, lined with monumental government & church buildings.
detail_description: Independence Square, also known as Plaza de la Independencia or Plaza Grande, is a grand plaza and park situated in the heart of old Quito. It serves as the focal point of Quito's historic district and features a monument commemorating those who first advocated for independence from the Royal Audience of Quito in 1809. The square is surrounded by monumental government and church buildings such as the Cathedral, Government Palace, Archbishop's Palace, and City Hall.
name: Independence Square
address: and Chile St Venezuela, García Moreno N5-16, Quito 170401, Ecuador

detail_description: Nestled within the historic convent of San Francisco in Quito, the Museo Franciscano Fray Pedro Gocial is a treasure trove of religious art that spans from the 16th to the 18th century. This captivating museum showcases around 300 exquisite pieces, including paintings, sculptures, and textiles that reflect the rich Catholic heritage and artistic prowess of Quito's past. Visitors can explore various themed exhibition rooms such as the Gallery of St. Francis' Life and Canvas Hall dedicated to St.
name: Museo Franciscano Fray Pedro Gocial

excerpt: Small museum in a 1565 hospital featuring exhibits about Quito's history & a tranquil courtyard.
detail_description: The Museum of the City, situated in the historic center of Quito within the old San Juan de Dios Hospital, offers a glimpse into the city's history and cultural heritage. Housed in a colonial building, it features exhibits on Quito's socio-historical processes and geographical influence. Visitors can admire the impressive colonial architecture and explore a tranquil courtyard.
name: Museum of the City

excerpt: Ecological reserve spanning across the mountainous landscape surrounding the Pululahua volcano.
detail_description: Pululahua Geobotanical Reserve is a captivating ecological reserve located northwest of Quito, spanning the mountainous landscape around the Pululahua volcano. This unique site is home to one of only two inhabited volcanic calderas in the world, where farming activities take place to sustain the local population and generate profit.
name: Pululahua Geobotanical Reserve

excerpt: City park with an astronomical observatory, a statue of Simón Bolívar & a lake with boat rentals.
detail_description: Parque La Alameda is a charming city park located between the Old and New cities of Quito. It features an astronomical observatory, the oldest in South America, although its stargazing capabilities are hindered by city lights. Visitors can rent pedal and row boats to enjoy the lake within the park or partake in activities like cycling and jogging. The park also houses a statue of Simón Bolívar and offers a pleasant environment for leisurely walks.
name: Parque La Alameda

detail_description: If you're looking to dive into the vibrant culture and rich history of Quito, the Free Walking Tour Quito is an absolute must. Spanning around three hours, this engaging tour takes you through bustling local markets and significant historical landmarks, providing a comprehensive overview of the city’s highlights. As you stroll along with your knowledgeable guide, you'll gain valuable insights into Ecuador's heritage and contemporary life—perfect for first-time visitors eager to learn more about their surroundings.
name: Free Walking Tour Quito

detail_description: Casa Museo Guayasamín is a museum that was created from the home, studio, and art collection of Ecuadorean artist Oswaldo Guayasamín. The museum showcases his personal art collection and design features of the house, providing insight into the artist's influence over decades. Visitors can also explore the neighboring Capilla del Hombre, which focuses on Guayasamín's examination of the suffering of Latin America's indigenous poor.
name: Casa Museo Guayasamín
address: Mariano Calvache E18-94 y, Quito 170135, Ecuador

detail_description: Panecillo, a district in the heart of the city, is home to the iconic Virgen Del Panecillo statue. Pims, a restaurant located nearby, offers visitors an opportunity to enjoy local cuisine while taking in stunning views of the famous angel monument. Travel resources like Tripadvisor provide helpful tips on how to navigate to both the restaurant and the renowned landmark for an unforgettable experience.
name: Panecillo
